Root Cause: The error is caused by a null collection being passed to List<T>.InsertRange, which is not allowed and will throw an ArgumentNullException. Solution: Before calling InsertRange or similar list operations, validate that the collection parameter is not null. For example:
if (collection != null) { list.InsertRange(index, collection); } else { /* handle or log appropriately */ }
Alternatively, add null checks at the start of the method:
if (collection == null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(collection));
User Guidance: Ensure that any upstream logic constructing or passing the collection guarantees it is never null, or provide a default like an empty list.
